{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d11327b9-6408-41ac-9aba-78e48e28e5ad","content":"Create a `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Your server must use **stdio transport** (read from stdin, write to stdout). Ensure it doesn't write logs/debug output to stdout — use stderr instead.\n- VS Code will launch the process automatically when Copilot agent mode needs it.\n- If you'd prefer to run a published build instead, replace the args with `[\"path/to/MyMcpServer.dll\"]` (after `dotnet publish`).\n- You can also put the config in your **user-level** `settings.json` under `\"mcp\"` if you want it available across all workspaces.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"54da76d2-5512-4210-bfec-cd57812cc5a7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The file doesn't exist or is empty. That's fine — the user said they built it. I can still provide the configuration guidance based on standard patterns for a C# MCP server using stdio transport.","outputTokens":293},"id":"d63d2e2e-5248-414d-acae-2be15bfa69ec","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:51:47.470Z","parentId":"5d1346ce-5928-43cb-badf-d95c68c5fbdb"}
